    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="993"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d993">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/239.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Mexican Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexican Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 21, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just received telegram from Department of Foreign Relations of my country
                    which says it is urgent for General Sanjinés at Ojinaga to receive as soon as
                    possible arms and ammunition that are <pb facs="0872" n="756" xml:id="pg_756"/>
                    now detained at Marfa, Tex., so that he may make prompt and vigorous
                    preparations for any emergency.</p>
                <p>I shall be obliged to you if you would obtain from His Excellency the President
                    the special permit therefor, which will be duly acknowledged by my
                    Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Crespo.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
